<p id="d1e1846">Conceptually, a prediction interval for the future viral state 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e1849" display="inline" altimg="si32.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi mathvariant="script">I</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>i</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> can be obtained by two steps. First, obtain random samples from the distribution of the model errors 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e1867" display="inline" altimg="si53.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>w</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mn>1</mn>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mo>…</mo>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mi>w</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>n</mi>
     <mo>−</mo>
     <mn>1</mn>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. Second, for every sample of the errors 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e1899" display="inline" altimg="si53.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>w</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mn>1</mn>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mo>…</mo>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mi>w</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>n</mi>
     <mo>−</mo>
     <mn>1</mn>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, obtain a point forecast of the future viral states 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e1932" display="inline" altimg="si54.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="script">I</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. The prediction intervals for the future viral state 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e1945" display="inline" altimg="si54.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="script">I</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> can be obtained from the ensemble of point forecasts.
</p>
